Cambridgeshire, England":"英国坎布利其爾帕森 德洛福","lifeSummary":"当Sarah Ann de Parson于1254年出生在英国坎布利其爾帕森 德洛福时，她的父亲Sir Knight Richard de Parson28岁，母亲Lady Ann de Whitemere28岁。她和Thomas de Hill至少有1个儿子。她去世于1273年在英国英格兰戴文阿可明斯特享年19岁，埋葬在英国英格兰戴文阿可明斯特。"},"hr":{"1254–1273":"1254.–1273.","1254–1325":"1254.–1325","1273–1317":"1273.–1317","1226–Male":"1226–preminuo","1226–Female":"1226–preminula","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1325":"1325","1254":"1254.","1273":"1273.","1317":"1317","Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom","St John the Baptist of Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom","Nash, Shropshire, England":"Nash, Shropshire, England","Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England":"Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England"},"cs":{"1254–1273":"1254–1273","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1273–1317":"1273–1317","1226–Male":"1226–Zesnulý","1226–Female":"1226–Zesnulá","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1325":"1325","1254":"1254","1273":"1273","1317":"1317","Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","St John the Baptist of Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Nash, Shropshire, England":"Nash, Shropshire, Anglie","Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England":"Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1254–1273":"1254–1273","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1273–1317":"1273–1317","1226–Male":"1226–Afdød","1226–Female":"1226–Afdød","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1325":"1325","1254":"1254","1273":"1273","1317":"1317","Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom","St John the Baptist of Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Nash, Shropshire, England":"Nash, Shropshire, England","Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England":"Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England"},"nl":{"1254–1273":"1254–1273","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1273–1317":"1273–1317","1226–Male":"1226–Overleden","1226–Female":"1226–Overleden","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1325":"1325","1254":"1254","1273":"1273","1317":"1317","Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St John the Baptist of Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nash, Shropshire, England":"Nash, Shropshire, England","Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England":"Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"1254–1273":"1254–1273","1254–1325":"1254–1325","1273–1317":"1273–1317","1226–Male":"1226–Deceased","1226–Female":"1226–Deceased","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1325":"1325","1254":"1254","1273":"1273","1317":"1317","Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom","St John the Baptist of Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Axminster, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Nash, Shropshire, England":"Nash, Shropshire, England","Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England":"Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Parson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status name or nickname from Middle English <i>persone</i>, <i>persoun</i> ‘priest, parson’ (Old French <i>persone</i>). The status of medieval bearers of the surname is uncertain. Priests were generally known by a habitational name rather than by a surname denoting their role in the church. They were not allowed to marry, but doubtless many had illegitimate children, some of whom may have been given <i>Parson</i> as a surname. Some of the original bearers may have been given it as a nickname (compare   Priest  ,   Bishop  ,   Monk  ) or it may have been an occupational name for someone who worked for the parson (a shortened form of <i>Personesservaunt</i> perhaps).","English: in northern England and the North Midlands especially, it is often a variant of   Pearson  . For the change in vowel compare   Parr  .","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Pärsson</b>, <b>Pehrsson</b> (see   Pehrson  ) or   Persson  , patronymics from vernacular shortened forms of the personal name   Peter  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Persoon","meanings":["Dutch: nickname or status name from <i>persoon</i> ‘priest, parson’ (see   Parson  )."]},{"name":"Priest","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands): nickname from Middle English <i>pr(i)est</i> ‘minister of the Church’ (Old English <i>prēost</i>, from Latin <i>presbyter</i>, Greek <i>presbyteros</i> ‘elder, counselor’, comparative of <i>presbys</i> ‘old man’). It may have denoted someone with a pious manner or possibly for someone who had played the part of a priest in a pageant. It may occasionally have been used to denote someone suspected of being the son of a priest but evidence for this is lacking.","History: A John Priest is recorded as being in Woburn, MA, as early as 1675. The <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrim Digory Priest of the Netherlands died the first winter at Plymouth in 1620, leaving behind a widow who remarried and two daughters, who did not pass on the surname."]},{"name":"Parsons","meanings":["English: occupational name for the servant of a parish priest or parson, from the possessive case of Middle English <i>persone</i>, <i>parsoun</i> (see   Parson  ).","English: many early examples are found with the prepositions (e.g. Ralph <i>del Persones</i> 1323); these are habitational names, with the omission of <i>house</i>, hence in effect occupational names for servants employed at the parson's house.","English: post-medieval variant of   Parson  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>. Alternatively, <i>Parson</i> may be a shortened form of <i>Parsons</i>."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":5,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sarah Ann de Parson was born in 1254, in Parson Drove, Cambridgeshire, England, her father, Sir Knight Richard de Parson, was 28 and her mother, Lady Ann de Whitemere, was 28. She had at le